Perspectives on Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations had unsettled large parts of Asia.
A year ago, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly pompous "State Visit Plus" in Beijing, which China had hoped would mark the end of Trump's anti-Chinese campaign rhetoric.
A year later, China and the United States are embroiled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced America's "strategic engagement" with China with "strategic competition."
Moreover, the American, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today there is great uncertainty in the financial markets; growth is slowing down in China and Europe, and higher interest rates are starting to take effect in America.
The uncertainty about the future development of the nuclear negotiations with North Korea also casts a shadow.
What, then, are the prospects for Sino-American relations in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on reducing the bilateral trade deficit and the import decisions that China will make regarding this will be reached by March.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the timeline.
If each tariff were negotiated one by one, it could take a year.
However, if Chinese economic reformers were to choose a more drastic approach by gradually committing to the abolition of all tariffs and urging Americans to do the same, a quicker result could be achieved.
This would, however, go against Chinese trade officials who have been trained for decades to be reluctant, let alone generous, about giving things away.
The reform of so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively uncomplicated.
Nevertheless, a reform is something different from how contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice, even if there should be no specific provisions regarding technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is however extremely problematic.
Earlier agreements made under President Barack Obama’s administration could be reaffirmed.
However, their enforcement or pursuing legal action for violations remains a hopeless endeavor.
A potential mechanism involves subjecting relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international trade arbitration courts based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing intellectual property protection.
If China objects, it could develop its own international trade arbitration process based within China.
For this, it would have to invite qualified foreigners to its dispute panel to strengthen its international credibility.
No one has confidence in Chinese trade courts.
To meet its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent trade and civil chambers within its judicial system, even though the criminal chamber remains subject to political control.
The American concerns regarding the country's state subsidies under the "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be alleviated.
The fact is that all countries provide some level of state support to their domestic technology sectors, although this is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe maximum government support for a particular company, enforcement would be difficult to assess.
I am not optimistic that there will be an agreement in this area.
Maybe America just has to outcompete China by increasing public investments in research and development in areas like information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China offers tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
Over time, China might decide to take such a drastic step as agreeing to zero tariffs not only with the US but with all members of the World Trade Organization.
This would offer China almost irresistible opportunities to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to stem the trend toward protectionism.
In such a shift, China could invite the members of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) to include it, thereby overstepping the United States (which had withdrawn from the free trade agreement as one of the first actions of the Trump administration) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably nimble when it comes to exploiting political openings and market access.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China joining the TPP have diminished since Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's recent visit to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the US, China is likely to focus on reducing conflicts in its relations with other countries in general foreign and security policy in 2019.
In the relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a clear reduction in Chinese incursions into the territory of the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
Also, China hopes to ease tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) over the South China Sea through the accelerated negotiation of a "Code of Conduct".
Moreover, after the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India.
And China might start moderating its stance towards Taiwan, given the electoral setback suffered by President Tsai Ing-wen's Democratic Progressive Party, which advocates independence, in local and regional elections last month.
This would of course change radically if the US continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
There continue to be incidents at sea with the US in the South China Sea, and the conflict could intensify if the US more forcefully asserts their stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Across Eurasia, China will continue to implement its major project, the New Silk Road.
In recent months, however, the initiative has caused less political stir in China.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain terms, following Sri Lanka’s handover of the Hambantota port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns about the long-term financial sustainability of the New Silk Road.
2019, such triumphant announcements about the New Silk Road may be less frequent.
Furthermore, China is likely to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions rather than highlighting new institutions for international political action.
It will probably continue to present itself as a new advocate for the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More sober representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rules-based system, especially when the US consistently shows contempt for them.
While China tries to re-stabilize its relations with the US and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership will likely use 2019 to form a well-informed judgment on the future direction of US policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would in any way alter the new US strategy.
Although they have concluded that America's stance towards China has undergone profound changes, they remain uncertain about the exact form these changes take and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is warranted.
